{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"96c580","input":"#### **Limitations:**\n\n#### My analysis is a preliminary look into whether PM2.5 monitors are located in relatively lowerer pollution areas, rather than being located in areas that more broadly represent air quality conditions to which the public and environment would be exposed. I encountered several limitations during this preliminary analysis that constrain my conclusions, indicating additional research is necessary prior to investing oversight resources into this matter.\n\n#### The known limitations to my analysis follow:\n\n- ##### **1. The EPA May Not Intend Monitors to Represent Their County Administrative Boundaries** I compared modeled PM2.5 estimates at the monitors to county-level median PM2.5 estimates but I did not account for the varying sizes of counties or whether counties are even the appropriate adminstrative boundary to which the monitor-level estimates should be compared. After all, the Environmental Protection Agency's designation of attainment, maintenance, and nonattainment areas may span multiple counties. Further, the Environmental Protection Agency uses modeling and reports of industrial emissions to support its designations in areas not covered by a physical air monitor.\n\n- ##### **2. Regulatory Siting Requirements Were Not Evaluated** Federal regulations establish siting criteria for air monitors, including requirements related to distance from roadways, buildings, vegetation, and other physical features. These requirements may limit the ability of state and local agencies to place monitors directly in some high-pollution locations. I did not evaluate whether the monitors were located in compliance with regulatory siting requirements or whether alternative siting locations would have been feasible.\n\n- ##### **3. Monitor Purpose Was Not Considered** Air quality monitors may be installed for different regulatory purposes, including background monitoring, source-oriented monitoring, compliance monitoring, and population exposure assessment. Some monitors are intentionally placed in locations that represent regional background conditions rather than local pollution hotspots. I do not distinguish between monitor types in my analysis, meaning some monitors that I flagged for closer inspection may have been intentionally sited to serve these purposes.\n\n- ##### **4. Analysis Limited to a Single Year** I evaluated monitor performance during calendar year 2019 only. Air quality conditions and monitoring operations can vary from year to year due to meteorological conditions, emissions changes, or network adjustments. A multi-year analysis may help determine whether the patterns identified in this preliminary analysis represent persistent monitoring characteristics or year-specific conditions.\n\n- ##### **5. Additional Factors Not Evaluated** My preliminary analysis did not assess other factors that could influence monitoring representativeness, such as population distribution and proximity to emissions sources. Incorporating these factors could provide a more comprehensive understanding of monitor placement relative to areas of elevated pollution. Further, any analysis on monitor representativeness must also include the monitor design values, given a monitor's design value proximity to Clean Air Act thresholds at the date of installation is likely to incentivize whether the monitor is placed in a low pollution area. After all, monitors that support a nonattainment designation lead to significant administrative burden to state and local governments and financial burden to local industry.\n\n#### These limitations demonstrate that my findings should be interpreted as preliminary indicators of bias rather than definitive conclusions, providing only enough evidence to support additional research efforts. Addressing these limitations through additional analysis would help me determine whether the patterns I identfied in this preliminary analysis reveal monitoring gaps that warrant further oversight.","pos":2.96875,"type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"bbd184","input":"#### **Scope and Methodology:** \n##### My preliminary analysis evaluated whether state and local PM2.5 monitoring sites are located in areas that capture air quality conditions representative of the broader counties they are intended to measure. My analysis focused on the calendar year 2019, spanning all PM2.5 monitors in the contiguous United States. I compared modeled PM2.5 estimates at regulatory PM2.5 monitor locations to median county-level modeled PM2.5 estimates to determine whether monitors tend to report values that are consistent with surrounding  air quality.\n\n##### I obtained my results with the following six steps:\n- ##### **1. Extract and Clean Contiguous United States PM2.5 Air Monitor Data.** I used the EPA’s Air Quality System dataset to obtain the location and daily PM2.5 observations for state and local regulatory monitors operating at least one day in the year 2019. I cleaned this dataset to ensure consistent formatting of monitor identifiers, coordinates, and daily PM2.5 measurements. I filtered the dataset to only include monitors operating within the contiguous United States to ensure comparability with the alternative PM2.5 dataset used in a later analysis.\n- ##### **2. Extract and Clean Modeled PM2.5 Estimates at Monitor Locations** To evaluate the quality of modeled air quality measurements and to prepare to answer my objective, I incorporated an alternative PM2.5 dataset derived from satellite observations and machine-learning models. This dataset provided estimated PM2.5 concentrations across the contiguous United States at 1 kilometer resolution. For each monitor location and operating day in 2019, I used the alternative PM2.5 dataset to extract the estimated PM2.5 value corresponding to the monitor’s coordinates. \n- ##### **3. Assess the Quality of Alternative and Regulatory Data** Before using the alternative PM2.5 dataset to evaluate monitor representativeness, I assessed whether the modeled values correlate with measured PM2.5 concentrations at monitor locations. This step confirmed that the alternative dataset reasonably approximates ambient PM2.5 conditions.\n<img src=\"https://cocalc.com/blobs/paste-0.5092465672774819?uuid=4cd3d663-96ed-433c-b2cb-c3e5acbf7bc0\" width=\"40%\">\n<br>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:40px;\">\nSource: C_air_monitors_w_alt_data_QA_check.ipynb\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n- ##### **4. Estimate County-Level Daily Median Modeled PM2.5** For each day in 2019, I calculated the median modeled PM2.5 value across all raster cells located within each contiguous county boundary. I selected the median value to minimize bias introduced by extreme outliers. This analysis resulted in a dataset containing daily county-level median PM2.5 values for all counties in the contiguous United States. I paired each daily county median estimate with a unique county code identifer for later comparison to the monitor dataset.\n- ##### **5. Assign Monitors to Counties**  The assessed dataset from Step 3 did not contain unique county code identifers so I could not compare it to the daily county median estimates without additional processing. To enable comparison, I spatially associated each monitor with the county in which it is located. This allowed me to pair each daily monitor estimate with a unique county code identifer for later comparison to the daily county median estimate dataset.\n- ##### **6. Compare Monitor Location Estimates to County-Level Estimates** In this final step, I compared PM2.5 concentrations at each monitor location to the median PM2.5 value estimate for its county on the same day. For each monitor, I calculated the proportion of days during 2019 in which the monitor reported concentrations below the county median. I then categorized monitors based on the percentage of days they fell below the county median. This classification allowed me to identify monitors that may be persistently located in lower-pollution areas relative to surrounding county conditions. I furthered this analysis by assessing the impact of the possible underreporting bias between states.\n\n\n\n##### **Analytical Tools**\n\n##### I performed data processing and analysis using the R language within CoCalc's Jupyter Notebooks. My spatial processing was supported by packages including dplyr, tidyr, readr, terra, sf, exactextractr, and ggplot2. I used geographic operations to extract raster values, compute county-level statistics, and associate monitor locations with county boundaries.","pos":2.9375,"type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"f3cb14","input":"#### **Findings:** \n##### While 64 percent of PM2.5 monitors are in areas that generally represent county-level air quality, nearly 6 percent of monitors are in areas where PM2.5 concentrations fall below the county median at least 75 percent of the year. Geospatial analysis indicates that these monitors are in Maryland, North Dakota, Nevada, and Missouri. Their locations in these states may result in underestimates of representative air quality by approximately 15.0, 7.8, 3.7, and 3.6 percent, respectively. If monitor placement persistently understates ambient pollution levels, the Environmental Protection Agency could rely on data that underrepresents actual air quality conditions when assessing compliance with Clean Air Act standards and the public may be unknowingly exposed to elevated levels of pollution. <br>\n\n<div style=\"width:600px; margin:auto;\">\n\n\n<img src=\"https://cocalc.com/blobs/paste-0.2492699010140721?uuid=3c9d7a6d-da25-4b56-98fd-83995d5cf392\" width=\"40%\">\n<br>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:40px;\">\nSource: F_air_monitors_altvalue_county_median__altvalue_comparison.ipynb\n</p>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:60px;\">\nNote: 64 percent of the monitors in the above figure had 50 percent or fewer days <br> below their county median, indicating they generally represent their county air quality.\n</p>\n</div>\n\n<img src=\"https://cocalc.com/blobs/paste-0.7992555741270624?uuid=4317db04-ee24-46f3-ac50-63d11287d36c\" width=\"40%\">\n<br>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:40px;\">\nSource: F_air_monitors_altvalue_county_median__altvalue_comparison.ipynb\n</p>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:60px;\">\nNote: Maryland's monitors may underestimate PM2.5 by an average of 15.0 percent, <br>North Dakota by an average of 7.8 percent, Nevada by an average of 3.7 percent,<br> and Missouri by an average of 3.6 percent.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<br>\n\n##### Because a portion of the monitoring network appears persistently located in low pollution areas, additional research is warranted to determine whether the observed pattern reflects legitimate siting constraints or whether these monitors truly underrepresent ambient PM2.5 levels. This additional research should incorporate additional years of data, additional pollutants, an analysis of regulatory siting criteria, and an assessment of monitor design values relative to regulatory thresholds to determine whether further oversight work is appropriate.","pos":2.71875,"type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"febd17","input":"#### **Additional Results Discussion:**\n\n#### The figure below shows the strongest evidence that the overall monitoring network is appropriately sited. On 58.5 percent of all days for all monitors, the modeled PM2.5 value at the monitor exceeded the monitor's median county modeled PM2.5 value. The remaining 41.5 percent of all days for all monitors involved monitor underreporting relative to their county median modeled PM2.5 value. However, the distribution of the overreporting and underreporting shows significantly more overreporting spread relative to underreporting spread. This distribution demonstrates the underreporting still approximately represents the county air quality with few notable outliers. However, if underreporting is correlated with elevated design values at time of monitor installation or similar suspicious circumstances, additional oversight may be warranted.\n\n<img src=\"https://cocalc.com/blobs/paste-0.06981400944799598?uuid=f5d6c6f7-29ed-416b-aec1-25c6d928f234\" width=\"40%\">\n<br>\n<p style=\"font-size:12px; color:#666; margin-left:40px;\">\nSource: F_air_monitors_altvalue_county_median__altvalue_comparison.ipynb\n</p>\n\n</div>\n","pos":2.984375,"type":"cell"}
